  "prompt": "Do women lactate when they are pregnant?",
  "response": "Yes, some women can begin to produce small amounts of **colostrum** (the first form of breast milk) during pregnancy, typically in the second or third trimester. This is due to hormonal changes, particularly the rise in **prolactin**, a hormone that stimulates milk production. However, the production of larger volumes of milk is usually suppressed by high levels of **progesterone** and **estrogen** until after childbirth.\n\nHere\u2019s a breakdown of the process:\n\n1. **First Trimester**: Hormonal changes prepare the breasts for lactation, but milk production hasn\u2019t started yet.\n2. **Second Trimester**: Some women may notice **colostrum** leaking from their nipples, especially toward the end of this trimester.\n3. **Third Trimester**: Colostrum production increases, but full lactation is still inhibited until after delivery.\n\nNot all women experience leakage during pregnancy, and this is perfectly normal. If you have concerns about lactation or milk production, it\u2019s always a good idea to consult your healthcare provider.",
